      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_003_5",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Write n = 2ªb, where b is odd. It suffices to show that Xm = ... modulo 2ª and modulo b, for some m < n. For the former, we only need Xn-1 ≥ a, but clearly Xn-1 = n by induction on n. For the latter, note that Xm = Xm+1 = ... (mod b) as long as Xm- 1 = Xm = ... (mod (b)), where ¢(n) is the Euler totient function. By hypothesis, this occurs for some m < Ф (b) + 1≤ n. (Thanks to Anoop Kulkarni for catching a lethal typo in an earlier version.)",
        "bbox": [
          0.12781954407676258,
          0.3241279070962568,
          0.49060151260400175,
          0.45213293632769325
        ],
        "order": 10
      },
      {
        "id": "docling_exam_paper_en-file-putnam-archive_1997_Solutions_1997s_page_003_12",
        "observed_type": "text",
        "canon_role": "support_paragraph",
        "text": "Remark. The preceding argument uses implicitly the fact that for P a simple closed polygon in the plane, if we let S denote the set of points on or within P, then the maximum distance between two points of S occurs between some pair of vertices of P. This is an immediate consequence of the compactness of S (which guarantees the existence of a maximum) and the convexity of the function taking (x, y) € S x S to the squared distance between x and y (which is obvious in terms of Cartesian coordinates).",
        "bbox": [
